# gen129 (L20-deep / L16): EPISTEMIC counterfactual — the knowledge-sibling of
# gen128's control-flow counterfactual. "What would you conclude if you didn't
# know that <fact>?" HYPOTHETICALLY retracts a believed fact from the live KB,
# RE-DERIVES the last stated conclusion, reports whether it survives, then
# RESTORES the fact — footprint-free. Dependency made explicit by removal.

# Guard: nothing concluded yet, so there is nothing whose support to test.
> what would you conclude if you didn't know that socrates is a man?
< Ask me whether something holds first — then I can tell you what that conclusion rests on.

> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates).
> every man is a mortal
< Learned rule: mortal(X) :- man(X).
# This conclusion is DERIVED (man -> mortal), and remembered as the last goal.
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.

# Un-know the supporting fact and re-derive: the conclusion falls. Computed by a
# real retract+re-derive, not asserted.
> what would you conclude if you didn't know that socrates is a man?
< If I didn't know that socrates is a man, I could no longer conclude that socrates is a mortal — that conclusion rests on it.
# Non-destructive: the belief was restored, so the conclusion still holds now.
> is socrates a mortal?
< Yes.

# Honest: it will only un-know something it actually believes.
> what would you conclude if you didn't know that socrates is a dog?
< But I don't know that socrates is a dog in the first place.

# INDEPENDENT support: plato is a mortal both directly AND via the rule, so
# un-knowing one route leaves the conclusion standing — it can reach it another way.
> plato is a man
< Learned: man(plato).
> plato is a mortal
< Learned: mortal(plato).
> is plato a mortal?
< Yes.
> what would you conclude if you didn't know that plato is a man?
< Even without knowing that plato is a man, plato would still be a mortal — I can reach that another way.
